{"parse":{"title":"Summer melt","pageid":45121582,"revid":846490823,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Summer melt</b> is the phenomenon of prospective <a href=\"/wiki/College\" title=\"College\">college</a> students' <a href=\"/wiki/Motivation\" title=\"Motivation\">motivation</a> to attend college \"melting\" away during the summer between the end of high school and beginning of college.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-twsLATimes_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsLATimes-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-twsCSMonitor_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsCSMonitor-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-twsWashPost_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsWashPost-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-twsTime_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsTime-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> This phenomenon is especially prevalent in low-income <a href=\"/wiki/Minority_group\" title=\"Minority group\">minority</a> communities, where students who qualify for college and in some cases even register for classes ultimately end up not attending college because they lack resources, support, guidance, and encouragement.<sup id=\"cite_ref-twsSJMercury_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-twsSJMercury-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Support programs, particularly by colleges using nudge methods like messaging students via text message, have been found to reduce summer melt.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Summer_melt&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Ceja, Alejandra (July 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20150120073459/http://www.ed.gov/blog/2013/07/summer-melt/\">\"Summer Melt\"</a>. <i>Homeroom</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Education\" title=\"United States Department of Education\">United States Department of Education</a>. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.ed.gov/blog/2013/07/summer-melt/\">the original</a> on January 20, 2015<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">January 19,</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Homeroom&amp;rft.atitle=Summer+Melt&amp;rft.date=2013-07&amp;rft.aulast=Ceja&amp;rft.aufirst=Alejandra&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ed.gov%2Fblog%2F2013%2F07%2Fsummer-melt%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASummer+melt\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsLATimes-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-twsLATimes_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">LARRY GORDON, October 19, 2014, Los Angeles Times <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-college-melt-20141020-story.html\">Advisors work to freeze 'summer melt,' get students to college</a>, Retrieved January 19, 2015</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsCSMonitor-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-twsCSMonitor_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Stacy Teicher Khadaroo, AUGUST 8, 2014, Christian Science Monitor, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Education/2014/0808/Stopping-summer-melt-and-getting-more-kids-to-college-this-fall\">Stopping 'summer melt' \u2013 and getting more kids to college this fall</a>, Retrieved January 19, 2015</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsWashPost-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-twsWashPost_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Peg Tyre, August 29, 2013, Washington Post, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/she-the-people/wp/2013/08/29/why-some-students-are-no-shows-on-the-first-day-of-college/\">Why some students are no-shows on the first day of college</a>, Retrieved January 19, 2015</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsTime-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-twsTime_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Annie Murphy Paul, May 24, 2013, Time Magazine, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://ideas.time.com/2013/05/24/the-summer-before-college-is-critical-to-success/\">The Key to College Success: Summer -- Incoming freshmen can flounder in the months before becoming a college student</a>, Retrieved January 19, 2015</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-twsSJMercury-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-twsSJMercury_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Jennifer Andaluz, San Jose Mercury News, August 14, 2014, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.mercurynews.com/opinion/ci_26336333/summer-melt-low-income-kids-accepted-college-need\">Summer melt: Low income kids accepted to college need help to actually get there</a>, Retrieved January 19, 2015</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation interview\">Vedantam, Shankar (July 16, 2013). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.npr.org/2013/07/16/202566709/why-poor-students-college-plans-are-hijacked-over-the-summer\">\"Why Poor Students' College Plans 'Melt' Over The Summer\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/NPR\" title=\"NPR\">NPR</a></i> (Interview). Interviewed by Greene, David<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">January 19,</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=NPR&amp;rft.atitle=Why+Poor+Students%27+College+Plans+%27Melt%27+Over+The+Summer&amp;rft.date=2013-07-16&amp;rft.aulast=Vedantam&amp;rft.aufirst=Shankar&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.npr.org%2F2013%2F07%2F16%2F202566709%2Fwhy-poor-students-college-plans-are-hijacked-over-the-summer&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASummer+melt\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Castleman, B. L., &amp; Page, L. C. (2013). Can Text Messages Mitigate Summer Melt?. New England Journal of Higher Education, 2.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-9\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-9\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Castleman, B. L., Page, L. C., &amp; Schooley, K. (2014). The Forgotten Summer: Does the Offer of College Counseling after High School Mitigate Summer Melt among College-Intending, Low-Income High School Graduates?. Journal of Policy Analysis and Management, 33(2), 320-344.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-10\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-10\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Castleman, B. L., Owen, L., &amp; Page, L. C. (2016). Reprint of \u201cStay late or start early? Experimental evidence on the benefits of college matriculation support from high schools versus colleges\u201d. Economics Of Education Review, 51113-124.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-11\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-11\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.wsj.com/articles/college-admissions-officers-wont-just-chill-about-summer-melt-1502468367\">https://www.wsj.com/articles/college-admissions-officers-wont-just-chill-about-summer-melt-1502468367</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1273\nCached time: 20180908200304\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.060 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.081 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 240/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 3667/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 75/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 7085/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.023/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.5 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   63.343      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   63.343      1 -total\n 68.10%   43.135      1 Template:Cite_web\n  8.39%    5.314      1 Template:Cite_interview\n  2.57%    1.630      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:45121582-0!canonical and timestamp 20180908200304 and revision id 846490823\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"University_and_college_admissions"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Colleg